URL reference: https://cloudnativenow.com/editorial-calendar/best-of-2025/ebpf-the-silent-power-behind-cloud-natives-next-phase-2/
DateReviewed: 2026-02-04
Description: Today's article is on eBPF and how it is anticipated to be the power behind the next phase in Cloud Native's evolution. They explain that originally it was targeted at packet filtering (the PF part), but over time it has expanded to more things over time, acting as a sandbox that can perform actions at the kernel level, without the downside of crashing the system. We then pivot to what currently uses it - Service Mesh, Observability, Security and Networking, each with a para on each of them. We then move on to why eBPF is to important - it can replace sidecars for some things, it gives deep visibility into the system, and is both efficient and extensible. They make the argument that while it is transformational, it's also invisible to average uses. There are some downsides, which include complexity of writing eBPF friendly code, that the code is tied to kernel versions (and Win support is still in progress), and multiple approaches are emerging that are incompatible. 
BottomLine: Good high level overview of eBPF and its place in Cloud Native
